title: For Sale:  S&W M&P 38 Model of 1905, Fourth Change
postcontent:
Up for sale is a S&W 38 M&P Model of 1905 4th change.  According to this article, 458,300 were mfg. 1915 - 1942.  This gun, bearing S/N 542650, was manufactured in 1926 according to Roy at S&W.  The gun is nickel plated with either a 6 or 6.5 inch barrel.  The caliber, of course, is
38 spl.  This gun sat on a shelf for about the last 50 or so years and has not been shot in a long time.  I am happy to test it for any serious buyer.  In fact, I wouldn't mind the opportunity.  :thumbup: S&W says it is good with any modern ammo except +P.

The gun shows typical finish wear, particularly in the gate area.  I tried to take a photo of this but the shiny finish made it very hard.  
Anyway, I would say the finish is equivalent to or better than on most
84 year old guns. I am happy to allow a buyer to inspect.  Mechanically I am aware of no problems.

The gun also comes with a unique leather holster.  The holster is stamped "Biffar Chicago".  Under the flap is scratched "B. Norwood".  I do not know the story of how the holster and gun came to be a pair, but I must say they are quite a nice duo.

The price is $500 for the pair. I prefer FTF but will ship at buyer's cost.  I travel regularly and will be going the length of the state within the next month, so I can arrange a meeting.

This is a Mauser 95 receiver with a stripped bolt.  It is a Chilean Mauser, pre-1899.  Some of the most expensive work in building this up has been done. This is a small ring Mauser and would be acceptable for a 7x57 Mauser or whatever other caliber conversion would be suitable for a small ring Mauser.

This one still has its' serial number and the prefix is a G.  It has the anchor stamped in the receiver indicating that it was made at the DWM plant at Oberndorf. title: For Sale/Trade:  Japanese Handgun
postcontent:
"It is indeed a Japanese Type 26 (1893) revolver, some of which were still in use during WWII. That one may have been captured, but more likely was taken from a depot in Japan at the end of the war. The engraving is typical Japanese, so it is reasonable to suppose that either the first American owner or a subsequent one was stationed in Japan and had the engraving done there. After the war, the Japanese economy was in bad shape and Japanese engravers did such work at modest cost. In fact, that kind of engraving was often called "carton of cigarettes" engraving because that was the usual cost. Perhaps the grip work earned the Japanese workman another carton!

It is hard to tell the quality of the engraving, but it doesn't look bad. I suspect those grips may be real ivory. I think that grip could be repaired, but I would want to consult an expert in that area. My WAG is that the gun could easily bring $1000 or more, but I would defer to anyone who may be more expert in that area.

AFAIK, Kijiro Nambu had nothing to do with that gun, it being a bit before his time. It was a mixture of Western designs, but mostly is derived from the Austrian Rast-Gasser, with a little Smith & Wesson thrown in for good measure. The caliber is 9mm Japanese, which is not readily available, but .38 S&W can be used by trinning the rim down from the front.

A word of caution. To disassemble the gun, DO NOT PRY anything. The trigger guard can be unlatched at the rear, then swung down. This allows the sideplate to be swung to the side and back, exposing the mechanism."



I've had this gun for over 30 years. Looking to sell or trade.. The handle is indeed ivory, please email with any questions.

title: For Sale:  Model 1909 Aregentine Mauser
postcontent:
Model 1909 Argentine Mauser re barreled from 7.65 mm to .30-06. 

This great rifle was made in Germany for the Argentine War and is an extremely accurate shooters rifle great for hunting. It has been tapped for a scope and you would have to pay three times this price to get the same quality in a new non military rifle. My rifle was made by Berlin's Deutsche Waffen und Munitionsfabriken (DWM), one of the better-known German Mauser manufacturers at the time. This rifle has the Argentine Crest intact – many of the rifles that were imported in the 50,s had these beautiful crests ground off. To many collectors, this superbly made bolt-action military rifle represents the crown jewel of all Model 98 variants.

Description below on this rifle are excerpts from a writer with Guns & Ammo:

Fit and finish of the metal parts are beyond mere imagination. Few custom rifles these days are better finished, both internally and externally. In fact, the 1909 Argentine action became one of the favorites of custom riflemakers for decades. This was because it was not only extremely strong but also dimensionally correct and consistent. Some of the finest custom rifles made have 1909 actions at their core.

title: For Sale:  Kahr TP9 (9mm) with Novak night sights LNIB
postcontent:
I'm selling my near-new Kahr TP9 (9mm) with Novak night sights.  Package includes the original box and accessories as well as the factory standard 2 magazines.

The gun has 250 rounds through it.  I've merely saved you the trouble (and expense) of breaking it in :).

This is a perfect option for those with larger hands, or looking for a longer barrel and sight radius on their Kahr.  Or, perhaps those looking for a polymer pistol that is slimmer than a Glock/XD/M&P.

For more info, check out Kahr's website http://www.kahr.com/PA-1_9mm_tp.html

This is the 8 round capacity model, purchased new at the end of August this year.

This is a good candidate gun for a grip chop. All the polymer Kahrs use the same mag release placement throughout the size range, so smaller models can accept magazines from larger models. This *also* means that you can chop the grip down to a more compact length and use the magazines from the corresponding smaller model. Cutting a TP9 down to P9 size is a popular option, giving you the larger sight radius and muzzle control of the larger slide, but the smaller grip for easier concealment. 

The best part about grip chops on polymer guns is that it's easy to perform on your own with a hacksaw and some files. Anyone who is reasonably patient and handy with common tools should be able to make some clean work out of it.

I am willing to travel within an hour of Manhattan to make an exchange.

title: For Trade:  RE: FT: Free
postcontent:
It is not illegal to buy a firearm for someone as a gift as long as they are not otherwise prohibited from owning a gun. If someone first gave money to a third party for the explicit reason of buying a gun for him then that would be a straw purchase. As long as they are residents of the same state it is completely legal for someone to buy a firearm for someone else as a gift. 
If you don't believe me then do some research, there are several hits when searching in google for "gun as gift".

I really don't like doing this in a classifieds listing but felt it necessary to correct the information that was incorrect.
